The LZ-3 was a 1906 German experimental airship.  Only 1 was ever built and used mostly as a transport for royalty and other important people.  Declared obsolete, it was scrapped in 1913.  with a maximum speed of 45 mph and 2 84hp engines, it was significantly faster than it's predecessor, the LZ-2.  
NOTE: this airship never carried planes though I did put some onto my model just for fun.  The aircraft type is a rough model of Junkers D.1 from 1917.  So, if you are looking for a precise model, do not print and attach the planes.

NOTE: read all instructions and make sure you have the appropriate materials before trying this project. You may need two sets of hand at one point or another. If need help just posted your question/concerns to the comments.

  • PRINT ALL THE PIECES. you will need as following:

    • a. 3x 12 hole zeppelin ring full print.stl
    • b. 2x 12 hole zeppelin ring full with gondola(type C)V2.stl or 2 more 12 hole zeppelin ring full print.stl if you don't want a stand
    • c. 1x zeppelin cone 4 scale z by 1p5 fin print.stl
    • e. 1x zeppelin cone final print.stl
    • f. parts for the planes(1-2 planes, optional)
    • g.1x 12 hole zeppelin ring full engine 2(type A) V2 print.stl(if you don't want an engine mount print 1 more 12 hole zeppelin ring full print.stl instead!)

  • GATHER NON-PRINTED PARTS(dowels):
    You will need 12x 15in. x 1/8in. wooden dowels. and x1 19in. 3/8 in. wooden dowel. After obtaining these make sure all the 1.8in. dowels are exactly the same length. This can be achieved by trimming them with a razor blade. Then, take one of your 15in. trimmed dowels and put it in the middle of your 3/8 in. dowel. After this, slide on both of your nose cones until they are completely on the 3/8in. dowel. Finally,measure the space in-between the 1/8in. dowel and the nosecones and trim that distance off your 3/8in dowel.

  • ASSEMBLY:
    This is probably the hardest step. You will need to make a jig out of something to hold up and align all the pieces. I made one out of Legos. 2 pieces were used to hold up the 3/8 in dowel and zeppelin off the ground. Another 2 pieces were as a right angle to straighten the rings 90 degrees to a flat surface. These were basically just 2 square pillars that sandwiched each ring. Then I slid on the rings and the cones in the order that I wanted and popped on the 2 cones. After this, I marked where I wanted all of the rings to be on the 3/8 in dowel. After that, I took off the cones And 1 at a time carefully glued on the rings making sure I had the 1/8 in snap-in holes aligned. This can be done by using you Lego level as a guide, lining up each ring with a part of the Lego mount while using the Legos to keep the rings standing straight up and down(90 degrees to the working surface). Finally, I popped on the 1/8 in dowels pressing firmly until the "snap" in. If your 1/8in. dowels won't "snap" in and they are too lose you could super glue them in place. If it is too large consider sanding the dowels or the rings.

  • SKINNING:
    So, you have made it this far. At this point, You will need to "skin" your zeppelin. For this, you will need these materials.

    • hanger 9 ULTRACOTE thermal shrink wrap or any thermal shrink wrap. (preferably gray or white but the color choice is yours, these are used when people make RC model aircraft)
    • Hobby or clothes iron.
    • heat gun(highly recommended)
    • infrared non-contact thermometer(recommended)
      The exact instructions should be on the shrink wrappings package but the basic idea is to make a template out of paper if you have to cut holes for anything sticking out such as engines or mounting rings . You may want to have the wrap be longer than the "body" ( the part with 1/8in. dowels) so you can cut it into segments and fold the ends over the last 2 rings. Then, after that transfer that template to your shrink wrap by tracing it onto the shrink wrap and cutting the shrink wrap to the same size as the paper template. Next, shrink the ULTRACOTE over the zeppelin running the iron on a low setting over where the dowels touch the ULTRACOTE. You should have 1 "gap"(space in-between the 1/8in. dowels) where the seam of the ULTRACOTE is(this is where the 2 sides overlap). This is preferably the very bottom "gap". Then, use the heat gun to smooth out bubbles and further shrink the shrink wrap. If the heat gun causes any burn holes to form a small ULTRACOTE patch should seal the hole giving a polished look.

  • FINISHING TOUCHES:
    If you put on engine mounts now is the time to put on your "engines". For this simply use scrap 1/8in. dowels and glue them on with super glue. Next, make the gondolas to do this cut a 1in. dowel into a 1in. long piece. Then, cut that piece halves. If you're not putting on planes, simply glue them on the gondola with super glue and you are done. NOTE: be careful, the super glue dries extremely fast onto the ULTRACOTE (No time to readjust after the gondola touches the ULTRACOTE). If you are mounting planes print all of the plane parts and glue them together. The wings might need sanding to be able to fit onto the body. After that, glue on the half circles to the gondolas (make sure not to put the gondolas on until the planes are attached) At this point you can glue on the planes or put on 10mm rare earth magnet mount onto the half circles. If you use magnets you might need to design your own magnet mount. Then, glue nuts onto the planes so they can mount onto the gondolas with the magnet mount. Finally, you're done, with the zeppelin at least...

  • STAND:
    I won't go into detail with this as you should design your own stand based upon your purpose. First, you should run a string through the 2 mounting holes and tie knots at the end to secure it. Then, you can simply hang it on your wall or go further and make a stand. I hammer drilled into a concrete brick and then made a sort of a "bow" with a dowel using a zip tie on each end and really cranking down on the zip ties. The bow was pulled with a string between each zip tie. I then mounted my zeppelin onto the top of the "bow" and put the "bow" into the brick I drilled into. You can see the picture of my stand if you look at the full screen picture of my zeppelin on the mount.

Moving right along, adding some more convenience... This thing builds on the last version of the OpenScad Virtual machine by adding a few convenience functions: CUBE(size, center);
CYLINDER(r1, r2, h, center);
SPHERE(r); And a couple for the CSG operations as well: UNION(parts);
DIFFERENCE(part1, part2); I also changed the 'CSG' module name to 'EXEC' which seems more appropriate. So, now you can do this: EXEC(UNION([CUBE([10,10,10]), CYLINDER(r1=6, r2=5, h=12)]); That pretty much makes it look more like what you'd write in normal OpenScad. So, why bother? It's more direct, or 'imperative'. This style might match some people's style better than the strictly hierarchical way of doing things. If you want to get really technical, this style is like functional programming. Since almost everything, other than EXEC() is a function, without side effects, the 'functions' can be easily passed around as parameters to other functions and modules. Still don't have any variables, loops, and the like, but how hard could it be ;-) Also, it's fairly easy to build individual parts as simple arrays and just use them. At any rate, take a look at the 'test_openscad_vm.scad' file as it shows how to mix and match things. The 'target()' function uses the all new stuff. The 'wheel()' function does a mix and match of styles. This all might make more obvious sense in a couple more versions.

1) Download the files
2) Play with 'test_openscad_vm.scad'
3) Rejoice!

This is a self-assembling Dodecahedron / virus. It is based off the design in this video http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=X-8MP7g8XOE .

To have a complete figure one must print 12 of these pieces. Each piece contains holes for 10 1/8" diameter, 1/16" thick magnets (such as these http://www.amazon.com/Craft-Hobby-Neodymium-Magnets-3x1-5mm/dp/B0065O63BK ) The complete figure requires 120 magnets. Inside each magnet hole there is an engraving that signifies the pole of the magnet that should be facing upwards. This is critical to the self assembly process. So this is done correctly I recommend putting all 120 magnets end to end in a long chain. Then mark the top face of the top magnet with a marker and remove it from the chain. Do this until every magnet has been marked. For simplicity assume that the marked faces of the magnets are the positive pole and place that side upwards in any slot with a plus sign. Place the marked faces downwards in any slots with a minus sign inside. Depending on the precision of your printer you might need to glue them in. Now that your dodecahedron is all assembled place it in a jar and shake it to separate all the pieces. Continue shaking it until all the pieces find their spot and self assemble.

title: Team Fortress 2 Level One Sentry Gun

description.text:
The level 1 sentry gun from TF2. This model is incredibly accurate, being created directly from valve's model. The only changes I made to it were to allow for printing and to allow for the joints to move. As of now, the finished model will require a little sanding and glue, but I'll remedy this soon. This model makes an excellent desk toy or display piece, and is sure to end up forcing you to try to explain TF2 to someone! A must-have for Team Fortress fans and Engie mains.  
Don't forget to post a make of it if it turns out really well!
(edit) Now that I've got access to SolidWorks, I'm considering remaking this

It is pretty simple to put together.   
1 Print out all the parts to whatever scale you want. There are some small details and pieces, so try to go large if your printer isn't amazing. The single largest piece is the AmmoDrum, so make sure that fits in the printing area.   
2 Plan the assembly. Find a good picture of a TF2 sentry, and figure out where everything goes. The parts are also named, so that should help.  
3 Assemble the gun. Don't do any gluing until you know that everything is correct. Some parts may need to be filed/sanded to fit into place, especially the moving joints. You can make them as stiff or as loose as you need to. Oh, and the right and left part designation is correct when looking at the gun head-on.  
If you get stuck, I made a mistake, or something isn't right, let me know. Let me know what you think. Thanks, and have fun!

This is a rough or alpha design for a nose mounted UAV pan and tilt camera platform. Note this is not a gimbal. It's goal is to allow a UAV pilot to look up and over their wing and fuselage as well as down and under the fuselage or towards the ground with a hopefully unobstructed view. I'll be attempting to keep this project up to date as time allows. NEWS: 22SEP15
--ALRIGHT! The whole assembly has been recreated complete with tooth profiles and appropriate pinions. Now, i haven't had a chance to have this printed and tested. I literally just finished the design. It'll be about 2 weeks till i have a chance to test fit and gear meshing. NOTE: with every part update there's an "instructions" update.

The servo mounts are designed currently for a Vigor VSD-22YMB servo. It has similar dimensions to a Blue Arrow D50024MG and that's the servo i hope to size this to in the end but i have not been able to find a concise datasheet on my target servo. The design process started with basic sketches, to AutoCAD, to Inventor, to Fusion 360. Part of the design process was starting from software i recognized on ward into software more suited for 3D printing. A lot of this is a learning process about the software as much as it is about prototyping and refining my design. This is by no means a final design. Update: 14SEP15-Located and corrected issue causing bad repair of Pan Gear in Meshmixer 15SEP15- v2 of the Pan gear has been uploaded. It's designed to decrease failure rate and need for material in the 3D printing process. it needs to be structurally tested against the servo's weight and torque. May add in epoxy or hot glue to reinforce the servo. 16SEP15- They have teeth!! Also, the tilt mount on Pan Gear v2 now has an extended guide to prevent binding from pressure and torque exerted by the tilt drive gear.
  • Added in some drive gears. I don't have any design parameters on the servos spline though and i'm certain the tooth profile on the tilt gear needs tweaking so they're incomplete for now.
    • 18SEP15 - CAMERA MOUNT!!! alright so it's a rehash of a design i found relatively common on here for a board camera. This one I remixed from Mochaboy's PZ0420 / 600TVL Board Camera Housing. I've included an image of the relevant camera mount dimensions so others can fit their own on. sadly i first drew it all in imperial instead of metric.
  • Reinforced the connecting points on the pan mount and added some minor support to the Pan servo mount to help relieve possible tension from the servos mounting point from pressure against the gear. Still need to actually built though lol.
    • 22SEP15 - So I've replaced the older design with the new one incorporating a bunch of updates, most important of which are proper tooth profiles. The redesign was also done in mm so i updated the dimension image for the camera mount fitting. I've also included dummy servos in the assembly image. They are sized after a VSD-22YMB winch servo. They're dimensions are very close to the Blue Arrow D50024MG i plan to use. I hope to be making a few of these in different materials and especially difference methods. I found the standard method of printing same material supports only makes finishing the parts to proper fit an utter pain so I'll be looking for someone who uses disolvable support material for the next build as this will hopefully be a functional prototype. Known issues i need to address: to name a few
    -Test servo fitting and gear slide meshing
    -Attachment method to air frame
    -Explore alternate pan gear mounts, possibly a linear rail bearing design.

3D printable pieces used to build my Surveillance Sanitizer art pieces that I made for Yami-Ichi NYC 2015.

Outer caps should be printed in purple PLA using supports with the logo facing upwards. The supports can be removed much more easily by just yanking them out with some pliers instead of trying to remove 2mm supports fused to the logo when printed the wrong way. OpenSCAD file for this is included. Tails logo is GPL licensed, so this particular STL file is GPL licensed, just a head's up on that. Inner should be printed in white PLA with the top facing downwards. The USB drive slot angle is steep enough that there's no need for supports this way. The inner caps were made with Tinkercad: https://tinkercad.com/things/iiqidDmaJLK. Rubber o-rings for the inner caps can be acquired from McMaster Carr (part #9452K26): http://www.mcmaster.com/#9452K26. USB drives for the inner caps are the Sandisk Cruzer Fit: https://www.sandisk.com/home/usb-flash/cruzer-fit. They can slide into the slot and fit snugly, but using Loctite glue to keep in place can prevent future wear and tear by keeping it in place: http://www.loctiteproducts.com/p/sg_plstc/overview/Loctite-Plastics-Bonding-System.htm. Hand sanitizer bottles used were Walgreens brand, but almost all generic hand sanitizer manufacturers seem to share the same bottle design, including Target's store brand. Inner caps are designed to fit tightly on the bottle neck, but using some glue will help create an airtight seal and prevent sanitizer from evaporating. I used Gorilla glue, but it expanded while curing and may be causing tension between the inner cap and bottle neck. I would instead try something like Loctite's Plastic Epoxy Bonder: http://www.loctiteproducts.com/p/13/7/epxy_plstc_s/overview/Loctite-Epoxy-Plastic-Bonder.htm.

description.text: If you want the files right meow and just want information/data , skip to instructions tab to the right.

Update (7/17/14): Uploaded Release 3.1 because the new design puts more pressure on the release lever than body 2.0 so a reinforced lever was needed, especially if printed in ABS. Looks a bit better too I think. Update (7/15/14): New holster!!! Extra sleek for quick draws and retention! Just download holster body 3.0, the retention ring, and the new clip (NerfHolsterClip2.0.stl) and you're in business. I have not tested it yet, but when my printer's free I will. It should fit just like the old one because it was built off the old one.
I have also removed the body 1.0, release 1.0 and release 2.0 because they suck and the new versions replace them without any downsides IMO. Update (7/14/14): I have decided to release one last update on this almost abandoned project now that I have gone from noob to intermediate-advanced in my modeling abilities, and because my holsterbody2.0 broke. Give me a week, and there will be a much cooler holster body released. It EASILY blows away all other versions! UPDATE (7/17/13): I have uploaded the release 3.0 which features a larger surface and a indentation for your finger for ultimate comfort and speed in drawing. This one is noticeably better than 2.0. I designed this holster because I saw the vast array of Nerf accessories and complete Nerf guns on thingiverse, yet no holsters surprisingly enough. The design requirements were that it had to be lightweight, durable enough to last a week of running, hiding, jumping/climbing, and the constant impact tension forces along the plastic that touches the screws into the clip. It must also be made out of nothing but PLA (or ABS but PLA is more environmentally friendly), office/school materials, and the least easy component to find, scrap wood screws or something similar (check your local IT place, they probably have thousands of screws and would probably be more than happy to let 1, 10 or 100 of them go). Unlike the real SERPA holster, this has a closed end so that your darts don't fall out while you're running!

To Use:
Download:
NerfHolsterBody3.0.stl (100%infill, 1 shell, .15mm or thinner -- preferably .1 layer height) Note: .1mm layer height (recommended) will take about 8 hours to complete. Should use about 49g material even with 100% infill.
NerfHolsterClip2.0.stl (No longer based on the radio belt clip, print at something that makes sense. Preferably in ABS so it bends a bit more)
NerfHolsterRetentionRing.stl (100%infill, 1 shell, .2mm (or really anything))
nerfholsterrelease3.1.stl (Use with Body 3.0. 100% infill, 1 shell, .1-.15 layer height)
Assemble as pictured, put two 8-32 machine screws through the clip and out of the holster. Then put the rubber band around the release and bring it down in between the screws. Slide the Retention ring on, and tighten down the nuts. When the rubber band has been adjusted to be snug and such, you can clip the ends protruding through the retainment ring. Oh and tighten it down with appropriate nuts, and use proper length screws (about 1") or trim longer ones.
See pictures for speedy draw and/or use concepts. Have fun with the most badass nerf holster ever!

This case design uses direct connection of the RTL-SDR receivers to the Raspberry Pi and eliminates the USB extension cords inside the case. Both antennas are also mounted inside the case, thereby eliminating ALL external wires except the power cord! This greatly simplifies its use in the cockpit. The dimensions are 166mm x 84mm x 33mm. Approx. 6.5" x 3.25" x 1.5". The micro SD card is accessible without opening the case and there are holes to view the Raspberry Pi, GPS and WI-FI status lights. If you use a RPi3 you will have to drill a small hole to view the RPi3 power and activity LEDs.

• UPDATE - 10/28/15 - I added a STL file for the top without antenna recesses.

  • UPDATE - 9/23/15 - I uploaded new STL files for the top and bottom. I moved the fan location and changed the air exit holes in the bottom and moved the location of the RY835AI chip on the top to clear the antenna recess and the RPi GPIO pins.
    • With the fan running the hottest CPU temperature I've seen is about 105F, the fan also cools the SDR receivers. I was receiving 10 ground-based ADS-B 978MHz towers at 1,000" AGL! This thing ROCKS!!! I used the following parts from Amazon to build this Stratux ADS-B receiver. Raspberry Pi kit or the new Raspberry Pi 3 2 RTL-SDR Receivers or 2 NooElec NESDR Nano 2 SDRs RY835AI GPS/AHRS Chip (get from eBay) or a VK-172 Gmouse USB GPS 25mm x 7mm Fan Kapton Tape Anker Astro E3 battery In the airplane I use an Anker Powerdrive 2 car charger plug Anker PowerLine Micro USB Cables I use self-adhesive velcro to hold the battery to the bottom of the case if I use the battery. Hatchbox Blue 1.75mm ABS filament I used a Prusa i3 printer to make my case. The Raspberry Pi is centered in the case which allows space for the cooling fan and also permits the case to provide some amount of strain relief to the RPi micro-USB power connection due to the distance you have to insert the power plug. I plan on permanently attaching the power cord to the case with some RTV adhesive (or hot-melt glue) to avoid any chance of breaking the RPi power connector. I also plan on securing the 2 RTL-SDR Receivers to the case support with the same adhesive. After you remove the plastic shell from the SDRs I suggest you add some Kapton Tape or some other non-conductive material to the bottom side of the top receiver so it doesn't short against the bottom receiver. To prepare your antennas peel the sticker off the bottom then, using a small screwdriver, pry the metal base off, you will see the coax shield wire is not attached to the metal base and it could come in contact with the antenna wire and give you poor reception. I also didn't see a need to cram 6 feet of extra coax into the case, so I cut the coax to about 8" and soldered the wires to the appropriate place. Put the metal antenna base back on and add a small amount of adhesive to secure it to the bottom of the case (during final assembly!), to keep the folding mast alignment centered on the box for neatness. You can re-purpose the magnet on your workbench to hold up a photo of your airplane, you don't want the magnet in the cockpit anyway. The cooling fan is a 5 volt, 25mm x 25mm x 7mm fan. I plugged it across the 5v and GRD pins on the GPIO header. I oriented the fan to blow into the case, it may work just as well blowing out. I saw CPU temps of about 100F in direct sunlight on the black dashboard of the plane, so I think the fan is working great. I printed most of the other Stratux cases available on Thingiverse, but decided to design my own to incorporate all of the pieces and wires inside one box, like the commercial units ;). I also wanted a simple, 2 piece, flat, box that would fit on my Prusa i3 200mm x 200mm print bed. I did have a problem with warpage so I added rafts to the corners, which helped, but didn't eliminate all warpage. Good luck!

3D printed in Black Colorfabb PLA-PHA and the pad is printed in Taulman Bridge. In the pictures you see the first iteration, you'll find the model has changed. I printed the pad small the first time but you can scale it to about 1,3... 1,5... for bigger projectiles and rubbers, just be careful how it's sliced --ideally the thinnest circle in the Pad should be 2 layers thick and each circle steps one layer up (0.2mm) to the top surface-- check your slices and scale according to your layer thickness and nozzle diameter.  However, I find it's better to print the pad with rubber filament like NinjaFlex if you can, or make it out of leather, it holds projectiles in the center and provides better accuracy.  
The Slingshot itself is an easy print but I recommend at least 3 vertical shells, 5-6 bottom and top layers and 25%+ infill. 'Never Know...  
Assembly:  
Take two identical rubber bands and simply lasso them to the pad first. Then, the other ends of the rubber bands go through the Slingshot holes and loop around the top of the horns. That's all the assembly, now you need nice projectiles. Be careful ;)  
You also have the SketchUp model in the files if you want to modify it.  
Enjoy!

Are you setting up a Maker Space? Why buy tools when you can make many of the common tools using your new digital fabrication tools. I am actively involved in my local makerspace (www.makerspace307.org) and I know how quickly costs can add up when you are outfitting your space. This is a simple inexpensive knife you can make using a 3D printer. Total cost is under $0.50 using filament that costs around $22.00/KG and Stanley classic utility blades (No. 1992). I have designed the file for printing in PLA. If you print this in another material or use a different brand of blade please let me know how it worked. description.text: This is a remix of http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:409100. This assumes you have a modified XYZprinter that can accept spools other than the original cartridge. The original spool hanger by Ranh316 was too small for the spools I use, so I started over using his basic premise. The spools that I use have an inside diameter of 59mm. These are 2LB spools that I order from eBay. The hanger was beefed up to support the additional weight. Bearings and end caps for the spool were created to give the spool less resistance and give the spool a centered area from which to rotate instead of dragging the spool over a rounded surface. A hex recess was added to the hanger base to fit a 4" 1/4x20 bolt which then goes thru two bearing blocks that grip the spool and provide a smooth spool rotation. A small cutout is required in the top cover of the printer to keep the filament from slipping under the spool. I could have included a filament retainer in the print, but I had binding problems with the original version and found that an opening in the lid works better. Thread the filament from the right side of the spool as shown in the photo. Additional parts you will need are a 4" 1/4x20 hex head bolt. Two 1/4x20 nuts, optional washers. Two 5/8 OD 1/4 ID bearings. Note: Bearings are a press fit. Use a vice to press them in place. You will need to print two copies of the bearing block.

This will require supports since there is an overhang present.  
Print two copies of the bearing block.  
Bearings are pressed into place with a bearing press or vice as this is made to be have a very tight fit.   
You should cut a small rectangle in the lid of your printer to ensure the filament does not ride under the spool.  
Insert the 1/4x20 hex head 4" bolt into the recessed area of the spool holder and secure with one 1/4x20 nut.  
Place one bearing block on the bolt and then put the filament spool in place, securing with the other bearing block and one more nut.  
Tighten securely.   Optionally, you might want to use a wing nut on the outside end cap rather than a nut.  Would make it easier to swap spools.

title: "Pencil" Puzzler
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text: Many thanks Thingiverse for featuring this thing! Also, thanks for the "Alliance Of Magicians" heads up! :) An old pencil magic trick, designed to appear to chop a solid pencil into 3 pieces, then magically restore the pieces back together. Video is here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zgqfPC3dVBA. I built my first version of this thing out of bass wood and "laddie" pencils in my high school days. Plastic versions of the illusion are available in magic stores and on the web, but I decided to design and print my own. All pieces are printed, even the "pencil" pieces. UPDATE: At the request of many, I've uploaded "Assembly.stl".

Study "Assembly.skp" or "Assembly.stl".  
Print and assemble all pieces as shown in "Assembly.skp" or "Assembly.stl".  
Test fit and trim, file, sand, etc. all parts as necessary for smooth movement of moving surfaces, and tight fit for non moving surfaces. Depending on the colors you chose and your printer settings, more or less trimming, filing and/or sanding will be required.  
Assemble as shown in "Assembly.skp" or "Assembly.stl".  
I used an indelible ink marker to add the pencil lead effect to the ends of all pencil pieces.  
Comment if you have questions.

comments.text: I will likely have the same issue, but for different reasons.  However, I think I see the issue.  About 1 inch from the top, a horizontal layer was created...it is hollow up until that point.
